-- 
Stocks in South Africa Fall for First Day in Five, Led by Anglo American

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-08-16T15:58:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-16/stocks-in-south-africa-fall-for-first-day-in-five-led-by-anglo-american.html
The FTSE/JSE  Africa  All Share Index
fell for the first day in five, easing 172.15, or 0.6 percent,
to 29,987.27 by the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo American Platinum Ltd. (AMS SJ), the world’s largest
producer of the metal, closed at a two-week high, rising 12.75
rand, or 2.4 percent, to 551.50 rand. Platinum rose for a sixth
day, reaching a two-month high of $1,824.50 an ounce.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (ANG)  , Africa’s largest gold
producer, closed at its highest since April 29, gaining 9.25
rand, or 2.9 percent, to 327.20 rand. Gold climbed for a second
day in  London  as concern over slowing economic growth boosted
demand for the metal as protection of wealth.  Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI)  , Africa’s second-biggest gold
producer, rose for a second day, adding 3.46 rand, or 2.9
percent, to 121 rand.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP)  , the world’s biggest mining
group, decline for the first day in five, dropping 4.13 rand, or
1.7 percent, to 234.36 rand. Copper fell in London on concern
about the outlook for demand after euro-area economic growth
weakened to the slowest pace in two years in the second quarter.  Capitec Bank Holdings Ltd. (CPI)  ,  South Africa ’s
fastest-growing bank, rose for a fourth day, gaining 2 rand, or
1.2 percent, to 173.75 rand. The lender said earnings per share
for the six months to Aug. 31 are expected to rise as much as 55
percent from a year earlier.  JSE Ltd. (JSE)  , the operator of Johannesburg’s stock
Exchange, rose the most in two months, gaining 2.99 rand, or 4.5
percent, to 68.99 rand. The company said it will pay a special
dividend of 2.10 rand a share.  Sasol Ltd. (SOL)  , the world’s largest maker of motor
fuel from coal, retreated for the first time in four days,
falling 6.01 rand, or 1.9 percent, to 319.20 rand. Oil dropped
from the highest in almost two weeks in  New York  as investors
bet that signs of a slowing global economy indicate fuel demand
will falter.  To contact the reporter on this story:
